"Gan J., Smith C.T.","A comparative analysis of woody biomass and coal for electricity generation under various CO2 emission reductions and taxes",2006,"Biomass and Bioenergy","30","4",,"296","303",,,10.1016/j.biombioe.2005.07.006,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33644885291&partnerID=40&md5=38bcdfe762309a65ae96542b849af529","Department of Forest Science, Texas A and M University, College Station, TX 77843-2135, United States; Faculty of Forestry, University of Toronto, Toronto, Ont. M5S 3B3, Canada","Gan, J., Department of Forest Science, Texas A and M University, College Station, TX 77843-2135, United States; Smith, C.T., Faculty of Forestry, University of Toronto, Toronto, Ont. M5S 3B3, Canada","Mitigating global climate change via CO2 emission control and taxation is likely to enhance the economic potential of bioenergy production and utilization. This study investigated the cost competitiveness of woody biomass for electricity production in the US under alternative CO2 emission reductions and taxes. We first simulated changes in the price of coal for electricity production due to CO2 emission reductions and taxation using a computable general equilibrium model. Then, the costs of electricity generation fueled by energy crops (hybrid poplar), logging residues, and coal were estimated using the capital budgeting method. Our results indicate that logging residues would be competitive with coal if emissions were taxed at about US$25 Mg-1 CO2, while an emission tax US$100 Mg-1 CO2 or higher would be needed for hybrid poplar plantations at a yield of 11.21 dry Mg ha-1 yr -1 (5 dry tons ac-1 yr-1) to compete with coal in electricity production. Reaching the CO2 emission targets committed under the Kyoto Protocol would only slightly increase the price of fossil fuels, generating little impact on the competitiveness of woody biomass. However, the price of coal used for electricity production would significantly increase if global CO2 emissions were curtailed by 20% or more. Logging residues would become a competitive fuel source for electricity production if current global CO2 emissions were cut by 20-30%. Hybrid poplar plantations would not be able to compete with coal until emissions were reduced by 40% or more. © 2005 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","CO2 emissions and taxes; Coal; Computable general equilibrium modeling; Electricity production; Woody biomass","Biomass; Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Coal; Logging (forestry); Taxation; CO<sub>2</sub> emissions and taxes; Computable general equilibrium modeling; Electricity production; Woody biomass; Electric power generation; Biomass; Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Coal; Electric power generation; Logging (forestry); Taxation; carbon emission; comparative study; pollution tax; Biomass; Carbon Dioxide; Forests; Power Generation",,,,,,"(2001) Climate Change 2001. Third Assessment Report of IPCC, , http://www.ipcc.ch/pub/reports.htm; Marland, G., Schlamadinger, B., Forests for carbon sequestration or fossil fuel substitution? A sensitivity analysis (1996) Biomass and Bioenergy, 13 (6), pp. 389-397; Schlamadinger, B., Marland, G., The role of forest and bioenergy strategies in the global carbon cycle (1996) Biomass and Bioenergy, 10 (5-6), pp. 275-300; Walsh, M., US bioenergy crop economic analysis: Status and needs (1998) Biomass and Bioenergy, 14 (4), pp. 341-350; Downing, M., Langseth, D., Stoffel, R., Kroll, T., Lange-scale hybrid poplar production economics: 1995 Alexandria, Minnesota establishment costs and management (1996) Proceedings of Bioenergy '96 - The Seventh National Bioenergy Conference, pp. 467-471. , Nashville, TN, 15-20 September. Southeast Regional Biomass Energy Program; Perlack, R., Geyer, W., Wood energy plantation economics in the Great Plains (1987) Journal of Energy Engineering, 113 (3), pp. 92-101; Perlack, R., Ranney, J., Economics of short-rotation intensive culture for the production of wood energy feedstocks (1987) Energy, 12 (